<subSubSection pageNumber="869" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="869">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="869">Note:</emphasis>
Grierson (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="869">Ceylon J. Sci., Biol. Sci.</emphasis>
11: 17-18. 1974), in a detailed study, rejected 
<specimenReference collectionCode="BM" specimenCode="15">
Herb. Hermann 2: 15, No. 312 (
<collectionCode>BM</collectionCode>
)
</specimenReference>
as a possible 
<typeStatus>lectotype</typeStatus>
as it conflicts with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
diagnosis, and appeared to argue in favour of 1044.1 (LINN) as the type. Unfortunately, the LINN sheet lacks a 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="869">
<volumeTitle>Species Plantarum</volumeTitle>
</emphasis>
number (i.e. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“1”">&quot;1&quot;</normalizedToken>
) and is evidently a post-1753 addition to the herbarium and not original material for the name. Oddly, Grierson later (in Dassanayake &amp; Fosberg, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="869">Revised Handb. Fl. Ceylon</emphasis>
1:81. 1980) referred to the Hermann material as type. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Anderberg’s">Anderberg's</normalizedToken>
choice therefore has priority.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
